{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bd21becd-328d-4506-84c7-18eb11097375","content":"There are two reliable approaches — both query the source of truth (your installed SDK), not docs.\n\n---\n\n### Approach 1: Query MSBuild properties from a project\n\nCreate a throwaway Android project and ask MSBuild directly:\n\n```bash\ndotnet new android -o /tmp/droid-probe && cd /tmp/droid-probe\n\n# Key properties the Android workload sets:\ndotnet msbuild -getProperty:AndroidSdkBuildToolsVersion\ndotnet msbuild -getProperty:AndroidDefaultTargetDotnetApiLevel\ndotnet msbuild -getProperty:AndroidCommandLineToolsVersion\ndotnet msbuild -getProperty:AndroidSdkPlatformToolsVersion\n```\n\nThese are the **exact versions** the workload expects. Use them in CI with `sdkmanager`:\n\n```bash\nsdkmanager \\\n  \"build-tools;$(dotnet msbuild -getProperty:AndroidSdkBuildToolsVersion)\" \\\n  \"platforms;android-$(dotnet msbuild -getProperty:AndroidDefaultTargetDotnetApiLevel)\" \\\n  \"cmdline-tools;$(dotnet msbuild -getProperty:AndroidCommandLineToolsVersion)\" \\\n  \"platform-tools\"\n```\n\n### Approach 2: Inspect the workload manifest directly\n\n```bash\nDOTNET_ROOT=$(dotnet --info | grep -m1 'Base Path' \\\n  | awk '{print $3}' | sed 's|/sdk/.*||')\n\n# Find the android SDK manifest\ncat $DOTNET_ROOT/sdk-manifests/*/microsoft.android.sdk.*/WorkloadManifest.json\n\n# This JSON lists every pack + version the workload ships.\n# The pack version tells you the Microsoft.Android.Sdk.<RID> version,\n# whose props files define the Android SDK component versions.\n```\n\n---\n\n**Approach 1 is best for CI** — it returns the exact strings you pass to `sdkmanager`, with zero parsing. Approach 2 is useful for auditing or scripting without a project file.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"acd636ab-1c1e-48b4-93b7-222fee4663dd","outputTokens":486,"requestId":"7FC9:3950:5F26C93:680E02B:69F15858"},"id":"0390b161-c064-481a-ac88-ab6bfb58353f","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:01:23.170Z","parentId":"369e0d12-589a-4a03-b30c-4d7ef4eccef5"}
